IS  - 1
SP  - 107
EP  - 130
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/10/11/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(91)90092-R
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030440769190092R
AB  - Social index numbers incorporate, either explicitly or implicitly, normative assumptions concerning the means by which the individual-level data is aggregated. Since the ethical underpinnings of the indexes can always be debated, a critical empirical issue is the extent to which aggregate index numbers vary with their underlying normative bases. We find that the cost of living indexes are surprisingly insensitive to the choice of the form of the index. However, the normative basis of the social quantity indexes has a dramatic influence on the measured level of the change in the standard of living.
ER  - 

